answer:   As an INTP, I would rate the extent of my agreement with the statement as follows:

7 - Strongly Disagree

As an INTP, I value efficiency and productivity, but I also recognize that everyone has their own unique approach to work and problem-solving. I believe that diversity in thinking and work styles is essential for creativity and innovation, and I would never dismiss or belittle someone for their different approach. In fact, I would be open to learning from others and incorporating their ideas into my own workflow, as long as they are logical and well-thought-out.

While I may get frustrated when I'm working on a project with someone who is not as efficient as me, I would never dismiss them or their contributions. I would instead try to find ways to work together more effectively, perhaps by dividing tasks or finding a compromise that works for both of us.

In summary, as an INTP, I value efficiency and productivity, but I also recognize the importance of collaboration and diversity in problem-solving, and I would never lose patience with someone who is not as efficient as me.

7 - Strongly Disagree

As an INTP, I tend to prefer independent and solo activities, rather than participating in group activities. I enjoy working on my own, exploring my own ideas and thoughts, and solving problems on my own terms. While I can appreciate the value of collaboration and teamwork, I often find group activities to be enervating and stifling, as they can involve too much socializing and compromise. While I value my alone time and prefer to spend time with a select few rather than a large group of people, I do enjoy meeting new people and exploring new connections.
